    <article class="argument-article">
      <h1 id="intro">How to construct and express academic arguments</h1>

      <div class="argument-lead">
        <p>
          If all authors agreed on everything, there would be no reason to write anything. One person could say
          everything there is to say. But in the social and commercial sciences, it does not work this way. There is
          much to talk and disagree about. The talking takes place around points where there are different perspectives
          and room for difference – which is what argument is all about. Unless there is an interaction between
          different ideas, there is no argument.
        </p>
        <p>
          In this document, we will focus on how to write such arguments. We will use the metaphor of a talk show to
          illustrate the process of argumentation.
        </p>
      </div>

      <section id="creating-a-talk-show" class="argument-section">
        <h2>1. Creating a talk show</h2>
        <p>
          Imagine you are a talk show host. You choose an issue to talk about in front of a live audience. Obviously
          you will select an issue about which you and your audience care, or which you can convince them to care about
          in the introduction to your show.
        </p>
        <p>
          But what kind of issue do you select? Probably one over which there are competing views. What kind of guests
          do you get to talk? Ideally those who have differences in views, so that you can get a lively conversation
          going. How do you get the conversation going? You will identify &ldquo;talking points&rdquo; – particular
          aspects of the issue where differences exist. If you select a good talking point, there will be no boring
          patches and uncomfortable silent moments.
        </p>
        <p>
          Do you form an opinion before the show? Most likely, because you would have done some research to help you
          identify the views. What do you do with your opinion? Since you care about the issue, you would obviously
          steer the conversation towards making your opinion look more convincing, but without coming across as biased.
          Instead of you disagreeing with the guests, it looks better if you have the guests criticise each other and
          use those critiques to steer the audience toward your view.
        </p>

        <h3 id="thinking-through-your-essay">1.1 Thinking through your essay like a talk show</h3>
        <p>
          This is almost the same way you will write your essay. You select an issue that you care about, and explain
          in the introduction why your readers should care about it. By transforming this problem into a question, you
          give your essay focus, and by stating your thesis, you help your readers to understand how all the arguments
          fit together.
        </p>
        <p>
          Then you read, and let the authors interact with each other inside your mind. You see how they say things
          that are connected to each other. You see the different issues (or talking points) and how the authors
          position themselves around every issue. You see how they criticise each other&rsquo;s positions. Over time,
          you develop your own position by &lsquo;listening&rsquo; to them interact with each other.
        </p>
        <p>
          I don&rsquo;t want to exaggerate the excitement of such a process, but it is quite intellectually stimulating
          when you engage in it properly. It can feel like you are reading a murder mystery – you change your mind as
          you discover new information and over time you settle on some suspect. Similarly, in your essay you start with
          a vague idea, and then find yourself swaying this way and that way, trying to make up your mind as you are
          exposed to different views. Eventually, a definite view starts to form in your mind, probably different from
          the one you started with, and you find yourself looking at the world through different eyes.
        </p>

        <h3 id="writing-your-essay-talk-show">1.2 Writing your essay like a talk show</h3>
        <p>
          When you write your essay, you want to give your readers the same sense of intellectual stimulation and
          discovery that comes with being exposed to different views and making up one&rsquo;s mind over time. You will
          do this by introducing them to your different &lsquo;talk show guests&rsquo; (the authors), their views (by
          summarising the relevant aspect of their views) and having these authors engage each other (although this is
          done by you, in your own words). You let the authors criticise each other on various aspects, and lead the
          readers to a conclusion – the conclusion you believe follows from their conversation.
        </p>
        <p>For example:</p>
        <blockquote class="argument-example">
          <p>
            Malthus (1798) argued that population growth will eventually outstrip the rate at which food can be
            produced, thus leading to famines and wars over scarce resources. This pessimistic view was criticised by
            many economists for not anticipating the possibility of technological advances (Friedman, 2002) and birth
            control (Thomas, 1998). However, in recent times, Malthus&rsquo;s predictions are becoming true, especially
            in developing nations. Technological progress is causing more problems – such as climate change and
            pollution – that are harming the quality of resources required for food production. In fact, Dixon (2008)
            predicts that very soon major wars will be fought over increasingly scarce resources such as water.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
        <p>
          Notice how, through my own words I am putting the authors in conversation, and leading them to a conclusion.
          It was easy to get the conversation going because I identified a &ldquo;talking point&rdquo; – an aspect
          where one group of authors (Friedman and Thomas) criticise another group (Malthus and Dixon). You can imagine
          them in a room – Malthus says one thing, Thomas and Friedman offer a critique, followed by Dixon supporting
          Malthus by addressing Thomas and Friedman&rsquo;s critique.
        </p>
        <p>You can almost imagine the talk show:</p>
        <div class="dialogue" role="region" aria-label="Talk show dialogue example">
          <p><span class="dialogue-speaker">You:</span> Let&rsquo;s talk about whether our planet&rsquo;s resources can continue to support us. What is your view, Reverend Malthus?</p>
          <p><span class="dialogue-speaker">Malthus:</span> I have been warning against this for centuries. As early as 1798 I explained that population growth will eventually outstrip the rate at which food can be produced, thus leading to famines and wars over scarce resources, because&hellip;</p>
          <p><span class="dialogue-speaker">Thomas:</span> I really think that is a bit pessimistic Malthus. Come on now, there has been no ecological crisis since you published your book. In fact, technological advances helped to significantly and consistently raise food production&hellip;</p>
          <p><span class="dialogue-speaker">Friedman:</span> And don&rsquo;t forget birth control which reduced population growth – something you did not anticipate at all Malthus!</p>
          <p><span class="dialogue-speaker">You:</span> But wait, just because Malthus&rsquo; prediction hasn&rsquo;t come true yet, does not mean it won&rsquo;t happen at all. Are we not seeing this very same technological progress causing more problems now – for example pollution – which is reducing the quality of our natural resources?</p>
          <p><span class="dialogue-speaker">Dixon:</span> If I may chip in here, I would like to support you in this. Good quality water is becoming increasingly scarce due to global warming and pollution. I predict that very soon major wars will be fought over increasingly scarce resources such as water – and probably other natural resources too.</p>
        </div>
        <p>
          The only difference between the talk show and the written argument is that you signal who is talking
          differently, and use a different kind of language (as explained in Section 4 below).
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="elements-of-an-argument" class="argument-section">
        <h2>2. Elements of an argument</h2>
        <p>
          This conversation between authors is an argument. We recognise it as an argument because there is an
          interaction between views and it makes a claim.
        </p>
        <p>
          Before you can write your own arguments (or script your talk show), you need to know what goes into an
          argument. Toulmin (1958)<sup><a href="#fn1">1</a></sup> identified the following elements that should appear
          in any good argument (also shown in figure 1):
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>There should be an explicit statement of the claim (C).</li>
          <li>The facts or evidence that directly supports the claim, which Toulmin refers to as data (D).</li>
          <li>An explanation of why the data is relevant in support of the claim, which Toulmin calls the warrant (W).</li>
          <li>The extent to which the claim can be accepted i.e. the qualification of the claim (Q).</li>
          <li>
            The conditions under which the argument might not be valid, also called the counterargument or rebuttal
            (R). The rebuttal can focus on the claim, the data or the warrant.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <figure id="toulmin-figure" class="toulmin-figure">
          <img src={figureSrc} alt="Toulmin model diagram: claims of previous arguments lead to data, then warrant with qualifier, leading to claim; rebuttal branches show challenges to claim, warrant, and data." loading="lazy" />
          <figcaption>
            Figure 1: Elements of an argument. Source: Adapted from Mitroff &amp; Mason (1980: 337).<sup><a href="#fn2">2</a></sup>
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h3 id="activity-1">Activity 1</h3>
        <p>
          Read the following paragraph/s in an article dealing with youth unemployment. Evaluate each attempt at
          establishing claim/s in support of the thesis.
        </p>

        <div class="attempts">
          <div class="attempt"><h4>Attempt 1</h4><p>Higher education institutions (HEIs) do not prepare graduates to become employable.</p></div>
          <div class="attempt">
            <h4>Attempt 2</h4>
            <p>
              The youth unemployment rate is 55% (Statistics SA, 2012). Higher education institutions (HEIs) do not
              prepare graduates to become employable.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="attempt">
            <h4>Attempt 3</h4>
            <p>
              The youth unemployment rate is 55% (Statistics SA, 2012). A quarter of these young people have studied
              towards a qualification at a higher education institution. Higher education institutions (HEIs) do not
              prepare graduates to become employable.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="attempt">
            <h4>Attempt 4</h4>
            <p>
              The youth unemployment rate is 55% (Statistics SA, 2012). A quarter of these young people have studied
              towards a qualification at a higher education institution (HEI). So it appears that HEIs play a role in
              graduates not being employable.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="attempt">
            <h4>Attempt 5</h4>
            <p>
              The youth unemployment rate is 55% (Statistics SA, 2012). A quarter of these young people have studied
              towards a qualification at a higher education institution (HEI). So it appears that HEIs play a role in
              graduates not being employable. However, Smith (2011:15) argues that individual characteristics are more
              important when it comes to determining employability.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="attempt">
            <h4>Attempt 6</h4>
            <p>
              The youth unemployment rate is 55% (Statistics SA, 2012). A quarter of these young people have studied
              towards a qualification at a higher education institution (HEI). So it appears that HEIs play a role in
              graduates not being employable. However, Smith (2011:15) argues that individual characteristics are more
              important when it comes to determining employability. While this is true, Jones (2010) showed that
              universities can change individual characteristics. This suggests that universities are indeed failing
              their graduates by focusing mainly on conveying generic subject knowledge rather than developing them as
              individuals.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 id="elements-summary">Herewith a summary of the elements of an argument</h3>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table class="elements-table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th scope="col">Element</th>
                <th scope="col">Question</th>
                <th scope="col">Notes</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <th scope="row">Claim</th>
                <td>What you want to say</td>
                <td>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Everything written must have a point (claim)</li>
                    <li>The main claim is your thesis – a view you want to take or a question you want to ask</li>
                    <li>All policies are claims successfully made through argument</li>
                    <li>Smaller claims are connected through argument to make up bigger claims, until the thesis is reached</li>
                  </ul>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <th scope="row">Data</th>
                <td>What is given</td>
                <td>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Generate empirical evidence to derive claims (induction)</li>
                    <li>Logically derive claims from given facts or axioms (deduction)</li>
                  </ul>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <th scope="row">Warrant</th>
                <td>So what?</td>
                <td>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Need to link data to the claim</li>
                    <li>Using transition and linking words</li>
                  </ul>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <th scope="row">Qualifier</th>
                <td>&mdash;</td>
                <td>
                  <ul>
                    <li>All knowledge is problematic and open to question</li>
                    <li>Express the degree of certainty with modal qualifiers</li>
                  </ul>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <th scope="row">Rebuttal (counter-argument)</th>
                <td>&mdash;</td>
                <td>
                  <ul>
                    <li>Counterarguments to claim, warrant or data used</li>
                    <li>Finding and rebutting counterarguments make your argument stronger</li>
                    <li>Conceding to rebuttals helps you to make your position more flexible</li>
                  </ul>
                </td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="counterarguments" class="argument-section">
        <h2>3. The importance of counterarguments</h2>
        <p>
          In your essay you will have different views coming together on different issues. Each view will have its
          proponents making their own arguments. As the writer of your essay, you will take a position, not only on the
          overall thesis, but also on the smaller issues that help you make your case. The answer to your question is
          your primary claim (or your thesis). To argue the thesis, you need to make smaller claims along the way which
          build up to your thesis.
        </p>
        <p>
          For example, suppose your thesis is: for FDI to lead to higher economic growth, a country needs to have high
          quality institutions in place. To argue this you will need to argue the following sub-claims: (1) FDI does not
          always lead to economic growth; (2) good institutions can promote economic growth; and (3) good institutions
          allow a country to obtain the maximum benefit from FDI. These three sub-claims are like the talking points that
          build up to your overall thesis.
        </p>
        <p>
          For each of these sub-claims you will marshal the evidence and explain how the evidence supports your view. But
          if you stop there your writing (or talk show) will be boring and lack credibility. Your ideas become stronger
          by making them compete against other views.
        </p>
        <p>
          In each of these sub-claims (or talking points) there will be different arguments, and you will obviously
          prefer those arguments that support your thesis. You can simply state your argument, but this will make your
          writing appear one-sided and uninteresting. To make your argument clearer and stronger, you should introduce
          the arguments of those who disagree with you, and then critique them.
        </p>
        <p>When critiquing those you disagree with, you can focus on any of the following:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>The claim (the author&rsquo;s claim is false)</li>
          <li>The qualifier (the author&rsquo;s claim is too strong or too weak)</li>
          <li>The warrant (the author draws the wrong conclusions from the evidence)</li>
          <li>The data (the author uses wrong or inappropriate data)</li>
          <li>The method (the method by which the author generated the data is wrong or inappropriate)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          You can criticise those with whom you disagree in your own voice, but this may not come across as credible. It
          is more credible if you use other authors to criticise those you disagree with.
        </p>
        <p>
          As an example, here is an extract from an actual student research proposal that helps illustrate how one
          handles counterarguments to strengthen one&rsquo;s own view. In her essay she was arguing that ethnicity plays
          an important role in influencing career choices. But along the way, she had to argue a number of smaller
          points – one being that different ethnicities had different traits. In this extract, she raises a
          counterargument (focused on criticising the method) and then shows that the claim of the counterargument is
          wrong.
        </p>
        <blockquote class="argument-long-quote">
          <p>
            Hofstede (2000) found that different ethnicities have particular cultural traits. Making use of surveys
            conducted among IBM employees in 72 countries, he identified five dimensions into which country cultures may
            fall. These dimensions were: power distance, uncertainty avoidance, individualism versus collectivism,
            masculinity versus femininity and long-term versus short-term orientation.
          </p>
          <p>
            His theory however was not without controversy and a number of studies questioned his theory (McSweeney,
            2002; Baskerville, 2003; Fang, 2003). McSweeney (2002) appears to have provided the strongest criticism. The
            main points of contention were Hofstede&rsquo;s method of research and that an organisation&rsquo;s culture
            i.e. that of IBM cannot be used to determine nations&rsquo; cultures. He also alleged that the data used from
            IBM was out-dated. McSweeney&rsquo;s criticism of the method of study arose out of the fact that in some
            countries Hofstede made use of sample populations that were too small to be representative of the entire
            population. In Pakistan for example, the sample size for the first survey was 37 employees and 70 for the
            second survey (McSweeney, 2002:94).
          </p>
          <p>
            While McSweeney&rsquo;s criticism that the sample size Hofstede used was too small is valid, it does not
            negate the final results concerning the dimensions found. Van Oudenhoven (2001) replicated Hofstede&rsquo;s
            results using a different and larger sample. The data he used was recent and therefore the problem of
            out-dated data McSweeney identified was dealt with. The fact that the dimensions remained true 20 years later
            among students rather than an organisational culture as criticised by McSweeney shows strong evidence that
            the people from different nationalities fall into particular dimensions showing cultural traits.
          </p>
          <p>
            The criticism of Hofstede&rsquo;s model has failed to discredit his theory; in fact, it has gained increasing
            support. His book has been cited in more than 26,000 publications since its publication. The general
            acceptance of Hofstede&rsquo;s model and its consistent replication (see Vaara, Sarala &amp; Stahl, 2012 for
            a recent example) offers strong support for the claim that different ethnicities and races possess different
            cultural traits.<sup><a href="#fn3">3</a></sup>
          </p>
        </blockquote>
        <p>
          The author could simply have argued the one side – maybe just writing the first paragraph, and leaving out the
          rest. While this would be fine in some cases, it is very dangerous not to engage the counterarguments if the
          issue is critical to your essay. The issue of whether ethnic groups have cultural traits was critical to her
          research proposal, but it is also controversial. Pretending that there are no alternative views would have
          left her claim open to severe criticism and made her look as if she was trying to hide something. By
          anticipating the criticism and addressing it, her argument immediately became stronger and also more
          interesting.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="talking-point" class="argument-section">
        <h2>4. Writing an argument about a particular talking point</h2>
        <p>Follow these steps when you write an argument:</p>
        <ol class="steps-list">
          <li>Identify an issue (talking point) within your larger essay where there are different views</li>
          <li>Summarise the different views fairly</li>
          <li>Decide who you agree with and how you will position yourself</li>
          <li>Determine what evidence you will call on to support your position and how the evidence warrants your position.</li>
          <li>
            Use the arguments of the view you agree with to critique the arguments of the view you don&rsquo;t agree with
            (based on claim, qualification, warrant, data or method)
          </li>
          <li>
            With all this at hand, write up your argument by letting the authors interact with each other and using
            appropriate argumentative language
          </li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          Steps 1–5 are the thinking steps (though it may involve some rough written work) and step 6 is the actual
          writing step.
        </p>
        <p>When you write up the argument, you can follow any of the following approaches:</p>
        <ul class="sequence-list">
          <li><span class="arg-seq">C → D → W → Q → R → Q</span></li>
          <li><span class="arg-seq">D → W → C → Q → R → C</span></li>
          <li><span class="arg-seq">R → C → D → W → Q</span></li>
        </ul>
        <p>There are other approaches too. Whatever approach you follow needs to be logical – that is really the only requirement.</p>
      </section>

      <section id="footnotes" class="argument-section argument-footnotes">
        <h2>Footnotes</h2>
        <ol>
          <li id="fn1">
            Toulmin, S. E. (1958). <cite>The Uses of Argument</cite>. Cambridge University Press.
          </li>
          <li id="fn2">Mitroff, I. I., &amp; Mason, R. O. (1980). Figure adapted from p. 337.</li>
          <li id="fn3">Illustrative extract from a student research proposal (abridged for teaching).</li>
        </ol>
      </section>
    </article>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .back-link {
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }
  .back-link a {
    color: var(--color-maroon);
  }

  .argument-layout {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: 2rem;
    align-items: start;
    max-width: 1100px;
  }

  @media (min-width: 880px) {
    .argument-layout {
      grid-template-columns: min(260px, 28%) 1fr;
    }
  }

  .argument-toc {
    position: sticky;
    top: 5.5rem;
    z-index: 1;
    padding: 1rem 1.1rem;
    background: #fff;
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: 10px;
    border-left: 4px solid var(--color-maroon);
    font-size: 0.88rem;
    line-height: 1.45;
    max-height: calc(100vh - 6rem);
    overflow-y: auto;
  }

  .argument-toc-title {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    color: var(--color-ink-muted);
    margin: 0 0 0.65rem 0;
  }

  .argument-toc-list {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    list-style: none;
  }

  .argument-toc-list > li {
    margin-bottom: 0.45rem;
  }

  .argument-toc-list ol {
    margin: 0.35rem 0 0.5rem 0;
    padding-left: 1rem;
    list-style: none;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .argument-toc-list ol li {
    margin-bottom: 0.3rem;
  }

  .argument-toc a {
    color: var(--color-maroon);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .argument-toc a:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  .argument-article {
    min-width: 0;
  }

  .argument-article h1 {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: clamp(1.45rem, 3vw, 1.85rem);
    color: var(--color-maroon);
    margin: 0 0 1rem 0;
    line-height: 1.25;
    scroll-margin-top: 5.5rem;
  }

  .argument-lead p {
    margin: 0 0 1rem 0;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--color-ink);
    max-width: 42rem;
  }

  .argument-lead p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .argument-section {
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
    padding-top: 0.5rem;
  }

  .argument-section h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.35rem;
    color: var(--color-maroon);
    margin: 0 0 1rem 0;
    scroll-margin-top: 5.5rem;
  }

  .argument-section h3 {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    color: var(--color-ink);
    margin: 1.75rem 0 0.75rem 0;
    scroll-margin-top: 5.5rem;
  }

  .argument-section h4 {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    margin: 0 0 0.35rem 0;
    color: var(--color-maroon);
  }

  .argument-section p {
    margin: 0 0 1rem 0;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--color-ink);
    max-width: 42rem;
  }

  .argument-section ul {
    margin: 0 0 1rem 0;
    padding-left: 1.25rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
    max-width: 42rem;
  }

  .argument-example {
    margin: 0 0 1rem 0;
    padding: 1rem 1.15rem;
    border-left: 4px solid var(--color-gold);
    background: rgba(212, 175, 55, 0.08);
    max-width: 42rem;
  }

  .argument-example p {
    margin: 0;
  }

  .dialogue {
    max-width: 42rem;
    margin: 0 0 1rem 0;
    padding: 1rem 1.15rem;
    background: var(--color-bg-alt);
    border-radius: 8px;
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
  }

  .dialogue p {
    margin: 0 0 0.65rem 0;
    max-width: none;
  }

  .dialogue p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

